        <h2 id="what-is">What is Machined?</h2>
        <p>Machined is an AI-powered SEO platform built around one core function: <strong>automated content clusters</strong> — groups of interlinked articles organised around central pillar topics. It serves 11,380+ users and was built by Sibu Ventures Ltd (UK) as a Paddle Launchpad partner.</p>

        <p>The product does five things:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Keyword discovery</strong> — surfaces hundreds of related terms from one seed</li>
          <li><strong>Cluster mapping</strong> — groups keywords into pillar + supporting topics</li>
          <li><strong>Cluster generation</strong> — drafts 30+ interlinked articles in one batch</li>
          <li><strong>Auto interlinking</strong> — contextual links between every article in the cluster</li>
          <li><strong>CMS publishing</strong> — pushes everything to WordPress or Webflow</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What Machined is <em>not</em>: a quality bar, a SERP-optimisation tool, or a human editor. It produces volume and structure. Rankings still depend on what you do after.</p>

        <h2 id="features">Machined features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>

        <h3>1. Cluster engine — the headline feature</h3>
        <p>Enter a single seed keyword. Machined returns a complete cluster map: one pillar topic and 25–40 supporting articles organised by semantic relationship. The mapping logic is genuinely well-designed and saves the 4–6 hours of manual cluster planning most teams do in spreadsheets.</p>

        <h3>2. Bulk article generation</h3>
        <p>Once you approve the cluster, Machined drafts every article in one job. Output is 800–1,500 words per article, with headings, intros, and contextual internal links pre-built. Generation typically completes in 60–120 minutes for a 30-article cluster.</p>

        <h3>3. Auto internal linking</h3>
        <p>This is where Machined genuinely shines. Every article ships with contextual links to other articles in the cluster, based on semantic relevance. The link structure follows pillar+spoke best practices — every supporting article points back to the pillar, and pillar links out to clusters of supporting pages.</p>

        <h3>4. CMS publishing</h3>
        <p>Direct push to WordPress and Webflow. The integration handles posts, categories, slugs, and the internal-link structure. Featured images are not generated — you add those manually or via a plugin.</p>

        <h3>5. Bulk regeneration + edits</h3>
        <p>If a generation run feels off, you can regenerate sections or whole articles. Useful, but burns credits fast.</p>

